{"run_id": "8eb3207c546d", "timestamp": "2026-04-28T19:24:43Z", "type": "adapter.tool_call", "agent": "product-manager", "data": {"message": "Calling tool: apply_patch", "tool": "apply_patch", "input": {"patchText": "*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: docs/product/login-page.md\n+# PRD: Login Page\n+\n+## Overview\n+Create the first authentication screen for Zenve so an unauthenticated user has a clear entry point into the product. This delivers a production-ready login page UI that matches the existing React design system and establishes the baseline auth experience without expanding scope into account recovery or registration.\n+\n+## Problem\n+Zenve does not yet provide a user-facing login screen. A user who needs to access the product has no defined entry page, no form to submit credentials, and no feedback states for authentication attempts. Without this screen, the authenticated product experience is blocked at the first step.\n+\n+## Users\n+- Unauthenticated operator: a user who needs to sign in to access the Zenve workspace.\n+\n+## Goals\n+- Give unauthenticated users a single, unambiguous path to start an authenticated session.\n+- Define the login UI contract so React development can begin without additional product clarification.\n+\n+## Non-Goals\n+- User registration or invite acceptance\n+- Password reset or account recovery\n+- Multi-factor authentication\n+- Social sign-in providers\n+- Session management after successful login\n+\n+## Requirements\n+\n+### Functional\n+- The product exposes a dedicated login page for unauthenticated users.\n+- The page displays inputs for email and password, a primary sign-in action, and a clear product title or identifier.\n+- The page displays inline validation feedback when either required field is empty at submission time.\n+- The page displays a submitting state that prevents repeated sign-in attempts while authentication is in progress.\n+- The page displays an authentication failure message when credentials are rejected.\n+- The page provides a clear post-success destination rule: after a successful login, the user is taken into the main authenticated area of the app.\n+- The page includes a secondary path for users who cannot log in yet, limited to contact/support guidance or placeholder text if no recovery flow exists.\n+\n+### Non-Functional\n+- The page follows the visual constraints in `.zenve/agents/react-developer/DESIGN.md`.\n+- The page is usable on mobile and desktop layouts without horizontal overflow.\n+- All interactive elements are keyboard accessible.\n+- Visible labels, error text, and button text are present in the UI and are not conveyed by placeholder text alone.\n+\n+## User Stories\n+\n+## Story: Sign in from the login page\n+\n+**As a** unauthenticated operator,\n+**I want** to enter my credentials on a dedicated login page,\n+**so that** I can access the Zenve workspace.\n+\n+### Acceptance Criteria\n+\n+- [ ] A public login page exists and presents email and password fields plus one primary sign-in action.\n+- [ ] Submitting the form with either required field empty keeps the user on the page and shows a visible validation message for each missing field.\n+- [ ] Submitting valid-looking credentials shows a loading state on the primary action and prevents duplicate submission until the request resolves.\n+- [ ] A failed authentication attempt keeps the user on the login page and shows a visible error message.\n+- [ ] A successful authentication attempt takes the user from the login page into the authenticated area of the product.\n+- [ ] The page remains functional and readable at mobile and desktop widths.\n+\n+### Out of scope\n+\n+- Registration, password reset, and multi-factor steps\n+- Persisting sessions across browser restarts\n+- Role-specific routing after login\n+\n+### Notes\n+\n+- For React implementation, follow `.zenve/agents/react-developer/DESIGN.md` for the split-layout auth treatment and high-density industrial styling.\n+- The authenticated destination can be a single default post-login landing route for this first version.\n+- If backend authentication is not yet implemented, the UI still needs explicit loading, success, and error states ready for integration.\n+\n+## Open Questions\n+- [ ] What exact copy should appear for the secondary help path: support email, generic contact text, or no link at all?\n+- [ ] What is the default authenticated landing page after a successful login?\n+\n+## Appendix\n+- Source of visual constraints: `.zenve/agents/react-developer/DESIGN.md`\n*** Add File: .zenve/agents/product-manager/memory/long_term.md\n+# Product Manager Long-Term Memory\n+\n+- 2026-04-28: Issue #1 is defined as a UI-only login page deliverable unless a broader auth flow is later specified.\n+- 2026-04-28: The repo currently contains product-agent scaffolding and React design guidance, but no application code yet.\n+- 2026-04-28: React auth and onboarding screens must follow the industrial control panel style in `.zenve/agents/react-developer/DESIGN.md`.\n*** Add File: .zenve/agents/product-manager/memory/scratch.md\n+# Scratch\n+\n+- 2026-04-28: Created `docs/product/login-page.md` and updated `PRODUCT.md` for issue #1.\n*** Update File: .zenve/agents/product-manager/PRODUCT.md\n@@\n-# Product: {project_name}\n+# Product: zenve-test\n@@\n-<!-- One sentence: what is this product and why does it exist? -->\n-_Not yet defined._\n+Zenve gives authenticated operators a workspace to access and manage the product's agent-driven workflows.\n@@\n-<!-- The single number that best captures whether the product is succeeding. -->\n-_Not yet defined._\n+Weekly active authenticated operators.\n@@\n-<!-- Define the personas who use this product. -->\n-\n | Persona | Description | Primary need |\n |---|---|---|\n-| _TBD_ | _TBD_ | _TBD_ |\n+| Unauthenticated operator | A user attempting to access Zenve for work. | A clear, reliable way to sign in. |\n+| Authenticated operator | A signed-in user working inside the Zenve workspace. | Fast access to protected workflows after login. |\n@@\n-<!-- Measurable goals the team tracks. -->\n-- _Not yet defined._\n+- Login page completion rate\n+- Authentication success rate\n+- Weekly active authenticated operators\n@@\n-<!-- MoSCoW-labelled backlog. Keep this list short and ordered. -->\n-- _Not yet defined._\n+- [MUST] Ship the first public login page UI so users can enter the product through a defined authentication entry point.\n+- [SHOULD] Define the default authenticated landing page reached immediately after successful login.\n+- [SHOULD] Define the support or recovery guidance shown to users who cannot sign in.\n@@\n-<!-- Ideas acknowledged but not committed. -->\n-- _Nothing deferred yet._\n+- [WONT] Registration, password reset, and multi-factor authentication for the first login-page release.\n@@\n-<!-- Unresolved product decisions. Remove when answered, add new ones as they arise. -->\n-- [ ] _What is the core problem this product solves?_\n-- [ ] _Who is the primary persona?_\n-- [ ] _What does success look like at 3 months?_\n+- [ ] What is the default authenticated landing page after login?\n+- [ ] What support or recovery path is available for users who fail to sign in?\n+- [ ] What does success look like at 3 months beyond the north star metric?\n*** End Patch"}}}
